\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There has been a rich debate in theoretical ecology on how to reconcile
 niche and neutral perspectives on species coexistence 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "gravel_reconciling_2006,carmel_using_2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Under the neutral perspective, all species have equal birth and death rates
 and compete equally (since space is limited) whilst under the niche perspective
, birth and death rates can vary between species and various mechanisms
 contribute to increasing intraspecific over interspecific competition 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hubbell_unified_2001"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 However, as it has been pointed out repeatedly, niche and neutral processes
 are not mutually exclusive: they may actually act together to produce observed
 species coexistence 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "gravel_reconciling_2006,mutshinda_what_2009,gotzenberger_ecological_2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An intriguing offshoot of the niche vs neutrality debate is the concept
 of `clumpy coexistence' 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "scheffer_self-organized_2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, whereby a simultaneous influence of both niche and neutral processes create
 several clumps of similar species along a single trait axis.
 Classical stabilizing niche differences (SNDs), such as a stronger net
 intraspecific competition than interspecific competition, enable coexistence
 of multiple clumps 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "chesson_mechanisms_2000"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, while within-clump coexistence occurs through neutral processes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hubbell_unified_2001,munoz_neutral_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, as species that differ too little in their fitnesses cannot exclude themselves
 out on reasonable timeframes.
 Indeed, clumps on the trait axis eventually thin out in absence of immigration,
 but transient coexistence can last for extended periods of time.
 This `emergent neutrality' within groups 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "holt_emergent_2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 has been proposed as a unifying concept for the niche and neutral theories.
 The findings of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "scheffer_self-organized_2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 have been disputed due to hidden niches in the original model 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "barabas_emergent_2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Hidden niches emerge through stronger intraspecific competition mediated
 by an additional intraspecific predation-like term 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "barabas_emergent_2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This makes coexistence in the Scheffer and van Nes model more similar to
 that of the classical Lotka-Volterra model 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "barabas_effect_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, so that coexistence within clumps is not exactly neutral.
 Still, the idea that niche and neutral assembly can mould communities stays
 potent 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "vergnon_interpretation_2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Since then, several studies have suggested that `clumpy coexistence' can
 occur in theoretical models, most notably models incorporating temporal
 variation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "scranton_coexistence_2016,sakavara_lumpy_2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In these temporal-variation models, equal competitive strengths are combined
 with other mechanisms like the storage effect (or temporal niche partitioning,
 that is an equivalent concept for forced Lotka-Volterra models, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "barabas_community_2012,scranton_coexistence_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 The storage effect increases the possibility of coexistence by making the
 interaction strength covary positively with a fluctuating environment (see
 also 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "barabas_community_2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, we build on the work of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "scranton_coexistence_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 to investigate the possibility of coexistence through species response
 to fluctuating environments.
 Our enthusiasm for the 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "scranton_coexistence_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 model stems from our interest in phytoplankton communities, that inspired
 their thermal preference curves modeling intrinsic growth rates.
 However, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "scranton_coexistence_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 described daily temperature as a random noise, i.e., independent and identically
 distributed Gaussian random variates over time.
 This appeared to us a key assumption to relax.
 Under most latitudes, temperature is indeed a seasonal signal, and seasonal
 forcing can strongly affect the dynamics of the community considered 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "vesipa_impact_2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Hence, over short timescales, random temporal variations often only add
 noise to a largely deterministic seasonal trend.
 Our present work can therefore be seen as an attempt to blend 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "scranton_coexistence_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

's stochastic framework with the periodic environments of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "barabas_community_2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, to better represent the mixture of stochastic and deterministic environmental
 forces affecting phytoplankton community dynamics.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because many phytoplankton species or genera respond in similar ways to
 temperature despite having different optimas 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "moisan_modelling_2002"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, we hypothesized that a large seasonal variation might not necessarily
 foster species coexistence.
 In fact, similar responses to seasonal fluctuations should lead to an increased
 synchrony of species abundances which, in turn, should theoretically mitigate
 the expected temporal partitioning.
 How seasonality affects coexistence (as opposed to a purely randomly fluctuatin
g environment) is therefore a key feature of this paper.
 In particular, we contrast cases where the storage effect is present vs
 absent, which conveniently maps to two different parameterizations of the
 forced Lotka-Volterra model.
 Moreover, the overall diversity obtained at the end of the simulations
 with 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "scranton_coexistence_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

's model was relatively low compared to what we usually observe in phytoplankton
 communities (several dozens to hundreds of species).
 We have therefore sought out which mechanisms would foster a truly species-rich
 community for extended periods of time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In an empirical study combining phytoplankton community-level time series
 and multivariate autoregressive models 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "barraquand2018coastal"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, we found that despite a large influence of the environment (including
 temperature, irradiance, and other factors), a strong intraspecific (or
 intragenus) competition, when compared to interspecific interaction coefficient
s, was most likely the key driver of species coexistence.
 In other words, strong self-regulation had a large role to play in maintaining
 species diversity in coastal phytoplankton 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "barraquand2018coastal"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 These high intraspecific interaction strengths mirror those found in a
 number of terrestrial plant communities 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "adler_competition_2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and in animal communities 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "mutshinda_what_2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, we therefore try to establish what are the relative contributions
 to coexistence of the storage effect vs strong self-regulation, in a phytoplank
ton-like theoretical community model.
 This led us to cross different combinations of seasonality in the forcing
 signal, presence of the storage effect or not, and intra- vs interspecific
 competition intensity, in order to disentangle the contributions of all
 these factors to biodiversity maintenance.
\end_layout

