\begin_layout Section
Discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have simulated competitive Lotka-Volterra dynamics forced by a fluctuating
 environment (e.g., temperature fluctuations) under a range of scenarios allowing
 more or less coexistence.
 Two coexistence mechanisms, the storage effect and strong self-regulation
 (i.e., intraspecific competition much stronger than interspecific competition),
 could be either present or absent, which led to four scenarios.
 These four scenarios were crossed with two possibilities for the forcing
 signal, a random noise (mostly white) and a stochastic yet seasonal signal,
 both with equal temporal variance.
 Our investigation therefore built on the model of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "scranton_coexistence_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, which included a random forcing and a storage effect, but considered seven
 additional combinations of mechanisms.
 This was motivated by our wish to include two observed features of phytoplankto
n dynamics: seasonal cycles 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "winder_annual_2010"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and strong self-regulation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "chesson_mechanisms_2000,adler_coexistence_2010,barraquand2018coastal"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Many mechanisms can lead to intraspecific competition being stronger than
 interspecific competition: nonlinearities in the functional forms of competitio
n or mutualism that contribute to increasing self-regulation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "kawatsu2018density"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, or predation as well as parasitism (see e.g., the generalist predators in
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "haydon1994pivotal"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Strong self-regulation seems nonetheless an ubiquitous feature in competition
 networks of primary producers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "adler_competition_2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, and perhaps even more general networks 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "barabas_self-regulation_2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before discussing the ecological interpretation of our results, we first
 recall some technical assumptions made in this study.
 All our simulations lasted for a fixed duration (5000 timesteps) as in
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "scranton_coexistence_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This means that short- and medium-term transients (a few years to hundreds
 of years) are completely negligible at the end of the time series, but
 very long transients can remain.
 We realized that convergence could be incomplete after 5000 years in some
 cases (e.g., random noise + storage effect + equal competitive strength).
 Such simulations would take up to 15 000 years to converge and the rate
 of convergence would slow over time, as can also be observed for similar
 models 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "scheffer_self-organized_2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 We kept a fixed time integration window rather than waiting for convergence
 for both technical and ecological reasons.
 From a technical standpoint, adding 10 000 years of numerical integration
 (or more) for the sake of reaching equilibrium would have been very computation
ally challenging, and comparison with the values reported by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "scranton_coexistence_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 would have been compromised.
 From an ecological standpoint, waiting for full convergence when there
 are extremely long transients 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hastings_transient_2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is also quite artificial: there is no reason to believe that very long
 transients (i.e., transients that maintains for thousands of years) has any
 less ecological reality than an attractor that is deemed stable because
 convergence has been reached.
 Speed of convergence is therefore an issue to judge whether transients
 should be considered or excluded, and very long yet fixed time window for
 integration allows advantageously to compare mechanisms for which speed
 of convergence might differ.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another assumption pertains to competition coefficients.
 To allow for comparison of our results with 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "scranton_coexistence_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, we took intra- and interspecific competition coefficients that were identical
 between species, i.e., there was no variance in 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{ii}$
\end_inset

 and no variance in 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{ij}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j.$
\end_inset

 By contrast, data-based coefficients vary to some degree 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "barraquand2018coastal"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, with a majority of weak interactions (as suggested in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "wootton_measurement_2005"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) and more variance in intraspecific coefficients.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "stump_multispecies_2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 recently considered the potential effects of competition coefficient variabilit
y (also called non-diffuse competition), as did 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "kokkoris_variability_2002"
literal "false"

\end_inset

; more variance in interspecific competition strength is usually detrimental
 to coexistence (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "stump_multispecies_2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for a classification of the various effects).
 Setting the coefficients using a multidimensional trait-based framework,
 like that of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ashby_competing_2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, would provide a natural development to the work presented here; it is
 in our opinion difficult to speculate on those variance effects because
 both intra- and interspecific competition coefficient variances may matter
 to community persistence.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With these assumptions in mind, we have found that first, temporally forced
 Lotka-Volterra dynamics cannot sustain any diversity with our phytoplankton-bas
ed set of parameters, unless the structure is geared to include either a
 storage effect or a strong self-regulation.
 Although this absence of diversity-enhancing effect of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pure
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 environmental variation has already been stated by other authors 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "barabas_community_2012,fox_intermediate_2013,scranton_coexistence_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, this is not always intuitive 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "fox_intermediate_2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, so we feel compelled to stress it once more: temporal variation in growth
 rate alone cannot help coexistence within competitive communities.
 A nice point made by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "scranton_coexistence_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 was that a built-in storage effect in a forced Lotka-Volterra model, parameteri
zed for phytoplankton communities, could lead to some degree of coexistence.
 Our investigation reproduced these results, using the random noise considered
 by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "scranton_coexistence_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 However, an arguably more lifelike noisy and seasonal temperature forcing
 considerably lessened the richness of the community after 5000 years, decreasin
g from 15 to 4 species on average.
 Even imagining that groups represented here are genera or classes rather
 than species, this is a fairly low diversity for a phytoplankton-like community
 (see Chapter 1 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "reynolds2006ecology"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 This suggests that the storage effect may not, on its own, be sufficient
 to maintain species-rich communities (e.g., dozens to hundreds of species).
 We have therefore sought out whether a stronger self-regulation could maintain
 a higher diversity, using field-based intra- vs intergroup (species or
 genera) competition strength ratio 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "barraquand2018coastal"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, where the intragroup density-dependence was chosen 10 times stronger.
 Implementing such strong self-regulation, in the forced Lotka-Volterra
 models that we considered, produced a higher level of diversity than the
 storage effect (almost double).
 Of course, the result is somehow contingent upon the strength of self-regulatio
n.
 Our estimates are a little stronger than what was found in perennial plants
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "adler_coexistence_2010"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, where interspecific competition was suggested 4 or 5 times stronger than
 intraspecific.
 Still, the widespread effects of natural enemies in phytoplankton (zooplankton,
 parasites) may contribute to increase the strength of self-regulation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "huber_role_2006,barraquand2018coastal"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 relative to other systems, hence we believe that 10 times stronger intraspecifi
c competition constitutes a reasonable order of magnitude.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, such strong self-regulation was still insufficient to maintain
 the whole community diversity (60 species) by itself, especially when the
 seasonal forcing (always decreasing species richness) was considered.
 The diversity within clumps of similar values of growth rates was considerably
 decreased once seasonality was implemented.
 This diversity reduction occurs because within a season, the signal autocorrela
tion gives long, contiguous time intervals to the best competitor to exclude
 its less adapted heterospecifics.
 This makes the results likely to hold not only for seasonal environments,
 but more generally for autocorrelated ones, i.e., 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

red
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 noise.
 This could be relevant for species whose population dynamics occur at timescale
s largely above one year.
 In contrast, the random noise – which can be considered white noise above
 the daily temporal scales – generates large temperature shifts more frequently,
 and thereby forbids such competitive exclusion.
 In a seasonal setting, a species with the highest long-term (arithmetically)
 averaged growth rate may not be the best competitor, and can disappear
 as a result of a strong competition from both low- and high-temperature
 tolerant species.
 This holds with or without a storage effect.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our results may appear at odds with recent proposals that seasonal forcing
 in itself would help maintain diversity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "sakavara_lumpy_2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 However, we compared the effect of seasonal forcing to that of other forcing
 signals while controlling for total variance.
 Thus, the contrast between our results and those of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "sakavara_lumpy_2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 may be due to the role of forcing variance over time (we compare scenarios
 under a constant total variance).
 Overall, while seasonality may be slightly better than no forcing at all
 in maintaining diversity, seasonal forcing of parameters does not improve
 coexistence: diversity within clumps is lower when seasonality is included,
 when compared to whiter noise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to community diversity, the biomass-trait relationship also
 varied from one simulation to another.
 Some regularities did emerge across simulations though.
 The storage effect begot several clumps along the trait space (as observed
 by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "scranton_coexistence_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 The seasonality that we added to the temperature signal led to more distant
 clumps on the trait axis (as said above, less species per clump).
 Conversely, strong self-regulatory mechanisms alone led to relatively uniform
 biomass distributions, with species forming a single large cluster, which
 covers a fraction of the initial trait space.
 Therefore, the shape of the distribution was affected by the coexistence
 mechanism at work while the average trait value was modified by the type
 of environmental forcing, even though the mean value of the environmental
 signal did not change.
 The biomass-trait distributions therefore constitute clues to interpret
 community dynamics 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "dandrea_challenges_2016,loranger_what_2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, although we certainly recommend to interpret them with caution to avoid
 over-generalization.
 The identification of multiple modes in biomass-trait relationships and
 SADs is relatively recent 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "dornelas_multiple_2008,matthews_multimodal_2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and is a rare pattern in theoretical models 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "mcgill_species_2007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "barabas_emergent_2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 convincingly argued that multimodality could arise from the demographic
 stochasticity of a single model run (with either self-regulation or neutrality,
 but without the clumpy coexistence emerging from a storage effect).
 However, our results are based on many model runs, for which either the
 storage effect alone or a storage effect + strong self-regulation in a
 seasonal context consistently produced multimodal distributions, while
 simulations without the storage effect always led to a single cluster along
 the trait axis.
 Our suggestion for empirical studies is as follows: if only one spatial
 location is observed, caution in interpreting multiple clumps on the trait
 axis is of course required, as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "barabas_emergent_2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 highlighted.
 However, with several locations - or in a theoretical context - one could
 average across locations to reproduce similar graphs to the ones produced
 here.
 Clumps in the trait axis when averaged across model runs/locations are
 therefore a signature of a coexistence induced by the storage effect, for
 the cases that we considered in the article.
 Of course, other mechanisms that we did not include in our models may produce
 similar patterns 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "rael2018emergent"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 or obfuscate these patterns – typically strong self-regulation weakens
 the clustering on the trait axis.
 We therefore view clustering on the trait axis (when averaged over several
 samples) as an interesting clue suggesting to look for a storage effect,
 rather than any definite proof that the storage effect is at work.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our previous empirical study of coastal phytoplankton dynamics 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "barraquand2018coastal"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, we did not find any storage effect (which does not mean that it could
 not be observed in other planktonic systems).
 Given the consequences of the storage effect for species richness and compositi
on presented here, we are skeptical that the storage effect could by itself
 help explaining phytoplankton diversity.
 However, our results suggest that in phytoplankton-like seasonal environments,
 even though empirically-based self-regulation produce much more diversity
 than the storage effect when considered in isolation, the storage effect
 can help diversity maintenance when combined to other mechanisms.
 Indeed, the combination storage effect + strong self-regulation is non-additive
: the cases were both self-regulation and the storage effect were present
 showed more diversity than generated by any mechanism on its own.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above results suggest the very exciting idea that multiple coexistence
 mechanisms might combine superadditively, thus helping us to better understand
 the astounding diversity of primary producers.
 This logic could, in principle, be extended to mechanisms that we have
 not considered here (e.g., spatial structure, specialized natural enemies,
 that could be as important here for plankton as they are for tropical trees,
 see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "bagchi_pathogens_2014,comita_testing_2014,barraquand2018coastal"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Previous research has however demonstrated that generalist seed predation
 could weaken the storage effect 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "kuang_coexistence_2009,kuang_interacting_2010"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 thus different mechanisms might not always combine superadditively as we
 found here.
 That said, superadditivity has been found in some cases, i.e., pathogens
 could enhance the storage effect 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "mordecai_pathogen_2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Better explaining plant or microbial diversity would then not be about
 selecting the best unique mechanism susceptible to explain the observed
 diversity, but rather better combining those mechanisms together.
 This may obviously be an annoyance for those who like to sharpen Occam's
 razor, but it clearly holds opportunities for theoreticians wishing to
 investigate synergies between coexistence mechanisms in highly diverse
 communities.
 Aside from the synergies between predator diversity-enhancing effects,
 strong self-regulation through various means and storage effects (on the
 temporal axis), one obvious follow-up of this research would be interactions
 with spatial structure.
 Spatial structure occurs both endogeneously, through spatially restricted
 movements and interactions, and exogeneously, through spatial variation
 in environmental covariates 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "bolker_combining_2003"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Numerous studies 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g.,"
key "bolker_spatial_1999,murrell_2002"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 have shown that spatially restricted movements and interactions - very
 small-scale spatial structure - can help coexistence, which we believe
 would be especially important for phytoplankton since many species form
 colonies (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "reynolds2006ecology"
literal "false"

\end_inset

; see discussion in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "barraquand2018coastal"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Moreover, although temperature is usually relatively spatially homogeneous
 over space, other drivers (e.g., rainfall, pH in terrestrial ecosystems;
 salinity in aquatic ones) may exhibit spatial variation which is a main
 factor for coexistence 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "snyder_when_2008"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The odds that different (resource) niches, natural enemies, spatial limits
 to competition and temporal niche partitioning all interact to promote
 the very high-dimensional coexistence observed in the field seem much higher
 than for any of those mechanisms alone.
 Whether the diversity-enhancing effects of these mechanisms combine subadditive
ly (as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "kuang_interacting_2010"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) or superadditively like here is therefore worthy of further research.
 
\end_layout

